\begin_layout Standard
The effect of defects and micro-structure on macroscopic properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stacking the tennis balls provides an example of the ordered crystalline
 arrays that most metals form.
 Is it possible for metals to have a completely disordered amorphous structure?
 Yes.
 But typically these are many-component alloys.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this demonstration, one base is aluminum (polycrystalline FCC), the second
 base has a 1/8”thick disc of amorphous metal alloy (Zr0.42Ti.14Cu.12Ni.10Be.22)
 glued to the aluminum.
 As the ball bearing bounces on the aluminum base, it loses kinetic energy
 to friction, heat and sound generation, and the formation of crystalline
 defects - slip and dislocation formation.
 The amorphous metal plate has a highly disordered structure – it is not
 a regular crystalline array – and these defects do not form.
 Hence less energy is transferred from the ball to the base.
 This explains why these alloys are used in state-of-the-art golf clubs.
 
\end_layout

